Histoplasmosis? & bats - Africa 19970212144846
Histoplasmosis? & bats - Africa (02) 19970213175638
Histoplasmosis? & bats - Africa (04) 19970219225228
[1
Date: 7 Jul 2000 11:15:32 -0400
From: Jaime R. Torres <torresj@mailandnews.com>

A large outbreak of acute pulmonary histoplasmosis recently occurred among
a group of secondary school students who visited two chambers of a cave at
a rural location of Miranda State, Venezuela, about 100 Km east of Caracas.
The "Alfredo Jahn" cave is the second largest in the country, being crossed
by a stream of water during most of the local rainy season, which lasts
from May to November. It has a horizontal development of 4,292 m and a 67 m
slope. Inner temperature ranges between 22 degrees C and 26 degrees C. The
cave is permanently inhabited by at least three species of bats, including
a common insect eating species (_Pterotnotus parnellii_), one omnivorous
species (_Phylostomus hastatus_), and a vampire bat (_Desmodus rotundus_).
A thick layer of bat guano covered the floor of the chambers visited by the
group, and the ground was noted to be dry.
Thirty four students and a teacher entered the cave to make observations
and collect samples of soil and rocks for a biology project. Twenty eight
students (17 females, 11 males; age range 15-18, median age 17) were
available for clinical and immunological evaluation. They remained in the
cave an average of 20 minutes. Twenty (71.4%) of the 28 students evaluated
became either acutely ill (64.3% of them) within 10-28 days (median 14
days); or else developed characteristic x-ray and laboratory abnormalities
(7.1%). The teacher, a 39-year old otherwise healthy male, also became ill
14 days after the exposure.
Sign and symptoms among the 18 ill students included fever (77.7%),
non-productive cough (72.2%), headache (66.6%), nausea and vomiting (50%),
rash (38.8%), abdominal pain (38.8%) asthenia (33.3%), chest pain (22.2%),
dyspnea (16.6%), myalgias (16.6%), and in one case (5.5%) erythema nodosum
or jaundice. Overall, 46.4% of the 28 students, and 65% of those who
developed clinical and/or laboratory abnormalities showed a positive
specific immunodiffusion test within 6-12 weeks.
--
Jaime R. Torres
<torresj@mailandnews.com>
José A. Suárez
